title: For Sale/Trade:  1923. Remington model 10-A, 26" barrel 12 ga, take down model
postcontent:
Made in November of 1923. Remington model 10-A, 26" barrel 12 ga, take down model. all numbers matching. Only 3500 of the 10-A were made. From what i have read, the 10-A models were used in WW2 by the USMC to train aerial gunners. However i see no ordnance stamps. For being 2 months short of it's 90th birthday this ol vet is in remarkable unrestored/ original condition. there is one small area of pitting on top of the receiver, but nothing too bad at all. It has 1 minor issue that prevents it from being used. A broken sear spring as seen in the pic below. It's a $10 part readily available online. The sear spring from a standard model 10 will interchange, from what i am told.

I am looking to trade for one of a couple of guns. In no special order i'd like an sks for the wife , a norinco is fine, she isn't picky at all.a Hi Point in .45 cal. only. The HP would need to come with ammo to help balance out the trade. I'd also like a single action 'cowboy gun' in .45 LC or .44 magnum. I'm not concerned about aesthetics, just that they cycle & fire properly.

The value as the 10-A sits now is $250-300 in the collectors circles. Restored and firing, $400-450. 

This was Remington's very first repeating shotgun. Introduced in 1908 and discontinued in 1929. This is an amazing piece of history & one any serious shotgun collector needs in their collection. 

I also want to ad this is a HUGE shotgun. In the pics below with me holding it, I'm 6'1" and 250lbs. I look like a kid holding 'daddys gun' ...lol. I picked this up last week & have decided it's just not the shotgun for me so i'm looking to trade out for something i will enjoy using.  What do you have?

Precision on the Range, at the Ranch, on Patrol or in the Woods. The Mini-14 name comes from the last American battle rifle issued in large quantity, the M14, a 9.2 pound, .308 Winchester caliber, U.S. service rifle produced from 1959 – 1964 in quantities exceeding 1.5 million units. It remained standard issue until about 1970. 

The Mini-14 itself has seen several design changes, a rework in 2003 and then a gas system tweak in 2005. Sometime between 2007 and 2008, the Mini-14 was revisited again, allegedly with new tooling, better tolerances and the current somewhat heavier profile, stiffer barrel to improve accuracy.

title: For Sale:  Black Hills MOLY COATED 168 gr Match Ammo for 308 Win.
postcontent: I have 5 boxes remaining of factory new / older stock Black Hills 168 grain HPBT Moly-Coated Match ammo.  That's 100 rounds total, 20 rounds per box, 5 boxes.  Moly coated bullets tend to reduce copper build-up in barrels, and the coating reduces friction and pressure as the bullet travels down the barrel, thus slowing down heat build-up, and allowing you to shoot for longer periods of time before groups start to wander from hot-barrel effects.  This stuff used to shoot remarkably well (consistently 1/2 moa or less) in one of my benchguns, but that particular rifle has been sold, and my last 308 benchgun happens to have a specific liking to Federals.  So I have no use for these anymore, but the ammo is excellent, and no longer easily found. It may have been too expensive for Black Hills to continue producing these bullets, and I think they stopped making them .  So here's a chance to pick-up some stock.  You may buy a single box, or purchase all 5, whatever one prefers.  This ammo when new cost over 2 bucks a round if I recall, but I will let them go here for 1.50 a round, or 150 bucks, which is about 45 cents less per round than Federal match.  So a decent savings for some very cool match grade rounds you can only find on the secondary market these days.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Carcano Rifle for sell/trade, Make Offer
postcontent:
A 6.5 1939 Italian Carcano. It has a aftermarket rear sight and could possibly be in need of repair. I bought the gun from a guy who had it since the 50's. He said it was great shooter and that he brought down several deer with it. I only put a few rounds through it. The first 10 or so went great, the next few wouldn't fire. I'm not sure if it was the ammo, a dirty bolt, or perhaps a firing pin/or spring issue. The ammo that wasn't firing did have a strike mark in the primer so it may have just not been hitting hard enough. 

The spring and pin are both easy to replace if it ends up being needed. Springs sell for $5 and pins for $20. 

The wooden stock has a wilderness scene with a deer carved into one side, cool if you like that sort of thing, not if you wanted it to be all original. I don't have any stripper clips for it but they are available on the market.
